{{Other uses|Chomeur (disambiguation)}}
The '''chômeur''', in the context of [[grammar]], is an element of a sentence that has been [[syntax|syntactically]] "demoted" from the nucleus to the periphery of a [[clause]]. The term comes from the [[French language|French]] word for "unemployed". In a [[passive voice|passive]] sentence, the [[agent (grammar)|agent]] is a chômeur, having been "demoted" from the central or nuclear function of [[subject (grammar)|subject]]. For instance, by changing the sentence ''Dogs attack the postman'' into ''The postman is attacked by dogs'', one transforms "dogs" into a chômeur.  The concept was introduced and used extensively in [[relational grammar]]. The term was suggested by the linguist [[Colette Craig]].

