In [[philosophy]], a ''razor'' is a [[principle]] or [[rule of thumb]] that allows one to eliminate ("shave off") unlikely explanations for a phenomenon, or avoid unnecessary actions.<ref>{{cite web |last1 = Garg |first1 = A. |date = 17 May 2010 |title = Occam's razor |url = http://wordsmith.org/words/ockhams_razor.html |work = A.Word.A.Day |accessdate = 2014-02-25 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140309141027/http://wordsmith.org/words/ockhams_razor.html# |archive-date = 2014-03-09 |dead-url = no |df = }}</ref>
Razors include: *[[Occam's razor]]: Simpler explanations are more likely to be correct; avoid unnecessary or improbable assumptions. * [[Paul Grice|Grice]]'s razor: As a principle of [[wikt:Special:Search/parsimony|parsimony]], conversational [[Implicature|implications]] are to be preferred over semantic context for [[linguistic]] explanations.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hazlett |first=A. |year=2007 |title=Grice's razor |journal=Metaphilosophy |volume=38 |issue=5 |page=669 |doi=10.1111/j.1467-9973.2007.00512.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Implicature |url = https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/implicature/ |work = Implicature, 5. Gricean Theory |accessdate = 2016-12-27 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161211042732/https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/implicature/# |archive-date = 2016-12-11 |dead-url = no |df = }}</ref> *[[Hanlon's razor]]: Never attribute to malice that which can be adequately explained by stupidity.<ref>{{cite web |title = Hanlon's Razor |url = http://catb.org/~esr/jargon/html/H/Hanlons-Razor.html |work = [[The Jargon File]] 4.4.7 |accessdate = 2014-02-25 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110430025318/http://catb.org/~esr/jargon/html/H/Hanlons-Razor.html# |archive-date = 2011-04-30 |dead-url = no |df = }}</ref> *[[David Hume|Hume]]'s razor: "If the cause, assigned for any effect, be not sufficient to produce it, we must either reject that cause, or add to it such qualities as will give it a just proportion to the effect."<ref> {{cite book |last=Miles|first=M. |year=2003 |title=Inroads: Paths in Ancient and Modern Western Philosophy |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iA8ZQX4jyHoC&pg=PA543&lpg=PA543&source=bl&ots=_5pdzt8_pi&sig=W6L-TpRfdvHkKmEPpXM7Ydfoy70&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t1ENU871KaSHygGE7oDIBg&ved=0CCgQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&f=false |page=543 |publisher=[[University of Toronto Press]] |isbn=978-0802037442 }}</ref><ref> {{cite book |last1=Forrest |first1=P. |chapter=Counting the cost of modal realism |editor1-last=Preyer |editor1-first=G. |editor2-last=Siebelt |editor2-first=F. |year=2001 |title=Reality and Humean Supervenience: Essays on the Philosophy of David Lewis |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g0QCcG99otoC&pg=PA93&lpg=PA93&source=bl&ots=ZqIJ_fPN02&sig=JkLuN09jqMtOZKfraOUsxt7XB6Q&hl=en&sa=X&ei=t1ENU871KaSHygGE7oDIBg&ved=0CCYQ6AEwADgK#v=onepage&f=false |page=93 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield Publishers]] |series=Studies in Epistemology and Cognitive Theory |isbn=978-0742512016 }}</ref> *[[Hitchens's razor]]: "What can be asserted without evidence can be dismissed without evidence." *[[Newton's flaming laser sword]]: If something cannot be settled by experiment or observation, then it is not worthy of debate.<ref name=NFLS>{{cite journal |author=Mike Alder |year=2004 |title=Newton's Flaming Laser Sword |url=http://www.philosophynow.org/issues/46/Newtons_Flaming_Laser_Sword |journal=[[Philosophy Now]] |volume=46 |issue= |pages=29–33 |doi= |access-date=2018-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204031512/https://philosophynow.org/issues/46/Newtons_Flaming_Laser_Sword# |archive-date=2017-12-04 |dead-url=no |df= }} : Also available as {{cite web |author=Mike Alder |year=2004 |title=Newton's Flaming Laser Sword |url=http://school.maths.uwa.edu.au/~mike/Newtons%20Flaming%20Laser%20Sword.pdf |publisher=[[University of Western Australia]] |work=Mike Alder's Home Page |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114041242/http://school.maths.uwa.edu.au/~mike/Newtons%20Flaming%20Laser%20Sword.pdf |archivedate=14 November 2011 }}</ref> *Popper's [[falsifiability]] principle: For a theory to be considered scientific, it must be falsifiable. *[[Sagan standard]]: Extraordinary claims require extraordinary evidence.
